208 //
209 // _EX_POOL_PRIORITY_ provides a method for the system to handle requests
210 // intelligently in low resource conditions.
211 //
212 // LowPoolPriority should be used when it is acceptable to the driver for the
213 // mapping request to fail if the system is low on resources. An example of
214 // this could be for a non-critical network connection where the driver can
215 // handle the failure case when system resources are close to being depleted.
216 //
217 // NormalPoolPriority should be used when it is acceptable to the driver for the
218 // mapping request to fail if the system is very low on resources. An example
219 // of this could be for a non-critical local filesystem request.
220 //
221 // HighPoolPriority should be used when it is unacceptable to the driver for the
222 // mapping request to fail unless the system is completely out of resources.
223 // An example of this would be the paging file path in a driver.
224 //
225 // SpecialPool can be specified to bound the allocation at a page end (or
226 // beginning). This should only be done on systems being debugged as the
227 // memory cost is expensive.
228 //
229 // N.B. These values are very carefully chosen so that the pool allocation
230 // code can quickly crack the priority request.
231 //
232 
233 typedef enum _EX_POOL_PRIORITY {
234  LowPoolPriority,
235  LowPoolPrioritySpecialPoolOverrun = 8,
236  LowPoolPrioritySpecialPoolUnderrun = 9,
237  NormalPoolPriority = 16,
238  NormalPoolPrioritySpecialPoolOverrun = 24,
239  NormalPoolPrioritySpecialPoolUnderrun = 25,
240  HighPoolPriority = 32,
241  HighPoolPrioritySpecialPoolOverrun = 40,
242  HighPoolPrioritySpecialPoolUnderrun = 41
243 
244  } EX_POOL_PRIORITY;

352 // begin_ntifs begin_ntddk begin_wdm begin_nthal begin_ntosp
353 //
354 // Routines to support fast mutexes.
355 //
356 
357 typedef struct _FAST_MUTEX {
358 
359 #define FM_LOCK_BIT 0x1 // Actual lock bit, 1 = Unlocked, 0 = Locked
360 #define FM_LOCK_BIT_V 0x0 // Lock bit as a bit number
361 #define FM_LOCK_WAITER_WOKEN 0x2 // A single waiter has been woken to acquire this lock
362 #define FM_LOCK_WAITER_INC 0x4 // Increment value to change the waiters count
363 
364  LONG Count;
365  PKTHREAD Owner;
366  ULONG Contention;
367  KEVENT Gate;
368  ULONG OldIrql;
369 } FAST_MUTEX, *PFAST_MUTEX;
370 
371 #define ExInitializeFastMutex(_FastMutex) \
372  (_FastMutex)->Count = FM_LOCK_BIT; \
373  (_FastMutex)->Owner = NULL; \
374  (_FastMutex)->Contention = 0; \
375  KeInitializeEvent(&(_FastMutex)->Gate, \
376  SynchronizationEvent, \
377  FALSE);
378 
379 // end_ntifs end_ntddk end_wdm end_nthal end_ntosp
380 
381 C_ASSERT(sizeof(FAST_MUTEX) == sizeof(KGUARDED_MUTEX));
382 
383 #if !(defined(_NTDRIVER_) || defined(_NTDDK_) || defined(_NTIFS_) || defined(_NTHAL_) || defined(_NTOSP_)) && !defined(_BLDR_)
384 
385 VOID
386 FASTCALL
387 KiAcquireFastMutex (
388  IN PFAST_MUTEX Mutex
389  );
390 
391 FORCEINLINE
392 VOID
393 xxAcquireFastMutex (
394  IN PFAST_MUTEX FastMutex
395  )
396 
397 /*++
398 
399 Routine Description:
400 
401  This function acquires ownership of a fast mutex and raises IRQL to
402  APC Level.
403 
404 Arguments:
405 
406  FastMutex - Supplies a pointer to a fast mutex.
407 
408 Return Value:
409 
410  None.
411 
412 --*/
413 
414 {
415 
416  KIRQL OldIrql;
417 
418  //
419  // Raise IRQL to APC_LEVEL and attempt to acquire ownership of the fast
420  // mutex.
421  //
422 
423  ASSERT(KeGetCurrentIrql() <= APC_LEVEL);
424 
425  OldIrql = KfRaiseIrql(APC_LEVEL);
426 
427 #if defined (_X86_)
428 
429  if (InterlockedDecrementAcquire(&FastMutex->Count) != 0) {
430 
431 #else
432 
433  if (!InterlockedBitTestAndReset(&FastMutex->Count, FM_LOCK_BIT_V)) {
434 
435 #endif
436 
437  KiAcquireFastMutex(FastMutex);
438  }
439 
440  //
441  // Grant ownership of the fast mutex to the current thread.
442  //
443 
444  FastMutex->Owner = KeGetCurrentThread();
445  FastMutex->OldIrql = OldIrql;
446  return;
447 }
448 
449 FORCEINLINE
450 VOID
451 xxReleaseFastMutex (
452  IN PFAST_MUTEX FastMutex
453  )
454 
455 /*++
456 
457 Routine Description:
458 
459  This function releases ownership to a fast mutex and lowers IRQL to
460  its previous level.
461 
462 Arguments:
463 
464  FastMutex - Supplies a pointer to a fast mutex.
465 
466 Return Value:
467 
468  None.
469 
470 --*/
471 
472 {
473 
474 #if !defined (_X86_)
475 
476  LONG NewValue;
477  LONG OldValue;
478 
479 #endif
480 
481  KIRQL OldIrql;
482 
483  //
484  // N.B. On x86 this code may need to be compatible with the legacy fast
485  // mutex code in an OEM HAL. The HAL code stores the owning stack
486  // pointer and not the owning thread in the fast mutex owner field.
487  //
488 
489 #if !defined (_X86_)
490 
491  ASSERT(FastMutex->Owner == KeGetCurrentThread());
492 
493 #endif
494 
495  ASSERT(KeGetCurrentIrql() == APC_LEVEL);
496 
497  //
498  // Clear the owner thread.
499  //
500  // N.B. The first operation performed on the mutex is a write.
501  //
502 
503  FastMutex->Owner = NULL;
504 
505  //
506  // Save the old IRQL and attempt to release the fast mutex.
507  //
508 
509  OldIrql = (KIRQL)FastMutex->OldIrql;
510 
511 #if defined (_X86_)
512 
513  if (InterlockedIncrementRelease(&FastMutex->Count) <= 0) {
514  KeSetEventBoostPriority(&FastMutex->Gate, NULL);
515  }
516 
517 #else
518 
519  OldValue = InterlockedExchangeAdd(&FastMutex->Count, FM_LOCK_BIT);
520 
521  ASSERT((OldValue & FM_LOCK_BIT) == 0);
522 
523  //
524  // If there are no waiters or a waiter has already been woken, then
525  // release the fast mutex. Otherwise, attempt to wake a waiter.
526  //
527 
528  if ((OldValue != 0) &&
529  ((OldValue & FM_LOCK_WAITER_WOKEN) == 0)) {
530 
531  //
532  // There must be at least one waiter that needs to be woken. Set the
533  // woken waiter bit and decrement the waiter count. If the exchange
534  // fails, then another thread will do the wake.
535  //
536 
537  OldValue = OldValue + FM_LOCK_BIT;
538  NewValue = OldValue + FM_LOCK_WAITER_WOKEN - FM_LOCK_WAITER_INC;
539  if (InterlockedCompareExchange(&FastMutex->Count, NewValue, OldValue) == OldValue) {
540 
541  //
542  // There are one or more threads waiting for ownership of the
543  // mutex.
544  //
545 
546  KeSignalGateBoostPriority((PKGATE)&FastMutex->Gate);
547  }
548  }
549 #endif
550 
551  //
552  // Lower IRQL to its previous value.
553  //
554 
555  KeLowerIrql(OldIrql);
556  return;
557 }
558 
559 FORCEINLINE
560 BOOLEAN
561 xxTryToAcquireFastMutex (
562  IN PFAST_MUTEX FastMutex
563  )
564 
565 /*++
566 
567 Routine Description:
568 
569  This function attempts to acquire ownership of a fast mutex, and if
570  successful, raises IRQL to APC level.
571 
572 Arguments:
573 
574  FastMutex - Supplies a pointer to a fast mutex.
575 
576 Return Value:
577 
578  If the fast mutex was successfully acquired, then a value of TRUE
579  is returned as the function value. Otherwise, a value of FALSE is
580  returned.
581 
582 --*/
583 
584 {
585 
586  KIRQL OldIrql;
587 
588  //
589  // Raise IRQL to APC_LEVEL and attempt to acquire ownership of the fast
590  // mutex.
591  //
592 
593  ASSERT(KeGetCurrentIrql() <= APC_LEVEL);
594 
595  OldIrql = KfRaiseIrql(APC_LEVEL);
596 
597 #if defined (_X86_)
598 
599  if (InterlockedCompareExchangeAcquire(&FastMutex->Count, 0, 1) != 1) {
600 
601 #else
602 
603  if (!InterlockedBitTestAndReset(&FastMutex->Count, FM_LOCK_BIT_V)) {
604 
605 #endif
606  //
607  // The fast mutex is owned - lower IRQL to its previous value and
608  // return FALSE.
609  //
610 
611  KeLowerIrql(OldIrql);
612  KeYieldProcessor();
613  return FALSE;
614 
615  } else {
616 
617  //
618  // Grant ownership of the fast mutex to the current thread and
619  // return TRUE.
620  //
621 
622  FastMutex->Owner = KeGetCurrentThread();
623  FastMutex->OldIrql = OldIrql;
624  return TRUE;
625  }
626 }
627 
628 FORCEINLINE
629 VOID
630 xxAcquireFastMutexUnsafe (
631  IN PFAST_MUTEX FastMutex
632  )
633 
634 /*++
635 
636 Routine Description:
637 
638  This function acquires ownership of a fast mutex, but does not raise
639  IRQL to APC Level.
640 
641 Arguments:
642 
643  FastMutex - Supplies a pointer to a fast mutex.
644 
645 Return Value:
646 
647  None.
648 
649 --*/
650 
651 {
652 
653  PKTHREAD Thread;
654 
655  //
656  // Attempt to acquire ownership of the fast mutex.
657  //
658 
659  Thread = KeGetCurrentThread();
660 
661  ASSERT((KeGetCurrentIrql() == APC_LEVEL) ||
662  (Thread->CombinedApcDisable != 0) ||
663  (Thread->Teb == NULL) ||
664  (Thread->Teb >= MM_SYSTEM_RANGE_START));
665 
666  ASSERT(FastMutex->Owner != Thread);
667 
668 #if defined (_X86_)
669 
670  if (InterlockedDecrementAcquire(&FastMutex->Count) != 0) {
671 
672 #else
673 
674  if (!InterlockedBitTestAndReset(&FastMutex->Count, FM_LOCK_BIT_V)) {
675 
676 #endif
677 
678  KiAcquireFastMutex(FastMutex);
679  }
680 
681  //
682  // Grant ownership of the fast mutex to the current thread.
683  //
684 
685  FastMutex->Owner = Thread;
686  return;
687 }
688 
689 FORCEINLINE
690 VOID
691 xxReleaseFastMutexUnsafe (
692  IN PFAST_MUTEX FastMutex
693  )
694 
695 /*++
696 
697 Routine Description:
698 
699  This function releases ownership of a fast mutex, and does not restore
700  IRQL to its previous level.
701 
702 Arguments:
703 
704  FastMutex - Supplies a pointer to a fast mutex.
705 
706 Return Value:
707 
708  None.
709 
710 --*/
711 
712 {
713 
714 #if !defined (_X86_)
715 
716  LONG NewValue;
717  LONG OldValue;
718 
719 #endif
720 
721  KIRQL OldIrql;
722 
723  ASSERT((KeGetCurrentIrql() == APC_LEVEL) ||
724  (KeGetCurrentThread()->CombinedApcDisable != 0) ||
725  (KeGetCurrentThread()->Teb == NULL) ||
726  (KeGetCurrentThread()->Teb >= MM_SYSTEM_RANGE_START));
727 
728  ASSERT(FastMutex->Owner == KeGetCurrentThread());
729 
730  //
731  // Clear the owner thread.
732  //
733  // N.B. The first operation performed on the mutex is a write.
734  //
735 
736  FastMutex->Owner = NULL;
737 
738  //
739  // Save the old IRQL and attempt to release the fast mutex.
740  //
741 
742  OldIrql = (KIRQL)FastMutex->OldIrql;
743 
744 #if defined (_X86_)
745 
746  if (InterlockedIncrementRelease(&FastMutex->Count) <= 0) {
747  KeSetEventBoostPriority(&FastMutex->Gate, NULL);
748  }
749 
750 #else
751 
752 
753  OldValue = InterlockedExchangeAdd(&FastMutex->Count, FM_LOCK_BIT);
754 
755  ASSERT((OldValue & FM_LOCK_BIT) == 0);
756 
757  //
758  // If there are no waiters or a waiter has already been woken, then
759  // release the fast mutex. Otherwise, attempt to wake a waiter.
760  //
761 
762  if ((OldValue != 0) &&
763  ((OldValue & FM_LOCK_WAITER_WOKEN) == 0)) {
764 
765  //
766  // There must be at least one waiter that needs to be woken. Set the
767  // woken waiter bit and decrement the waiter count. If the exchange
768  // fails, then another thread will do the wake.
769  //
770 
771  OldValue = OldValue + FM_LOCK_BIT;
772  NewValue = OldValue + FM_LOCK_WAITER_WOKEN - FM_LOCK_WAITER_INC;
773  if (InterlockedCompareExchange(&FastMutex->Count, NewValue, OldValue) == OldValue) {
774 
775  //
776  // There are one or more threads waiting for ownership of the
777  // mutex
778  //
779 
780  KeSignalGateBoostPriority((PKGATE)&FastMutex->Gate);
781  }
782  }
783 
784 #endif
785 
786  return;
787 }
788 
789 //
790 // The EX_SPIN_LOCK could be made a CHAR to save space - this would limit
791 // support to 127 processors since the high bit is used to denote exclusive.
792 // Thus we wouldn't want to export it this way, but could use this internally
793 // for structures that are tight on space (may get a lot of false cacheline
794 // pinging due to sharing though).
795 //
796 // At some point we may also want to do cache aware versions of these APIs.
797 //
798 
799 typedef LONG EX_SPIN_LOCK, *PEX_SPIN_LOCK;
800 
801 #if !defined (NT_UP)
802 
803 #define EXP_SPIN_LOCK_EXCLUSIVE 0x80000000
804 
805 FORCEINLINE
806 KIRQL
807 ExAcquireSpinLockShared (
808  IN PEX_SPIN_LOCK SpinLock
809  )
810 {
811  KIRQL OldIrql;
812  EX_SPIN_LOCK LockContents;
813  EX_SPIN_LOCK NewLockContents;
814 
815  KeRaiseIrql (DISPATCH_LEVEL, &OldIrql);
816 
817  do {
818 
819  LockContents = *(volatile EX_SPIN_LOCK *)SpinLock;
820 
821  //
822  // If the lock is not being sought exclusive by anyone then try for
823  // it shared now.
824  //
825 
826  if ((LockContents & EXP_SPIN_LOCK_EXCLUSIVE) == 0) {
827 
828  NewLockContents = LockContents + 1;
829 
830  if (InterlockedCompareExchangeAcquire (SpinLock,
831  NewLockContents,
832  LockContents) == LockContents) {
833  return OldIrql;
834  }
835  }
836 
837  KeYieldProcessor();
838 
839  } while (TRUE);
840 }
841 
842 FORCEINLINE
843 VOID
844 ExReleaseSpinLockShared (
845  IN PEX_SPIN_LOCK SpinLock,
846  IN KIRQL OldIrql
847  )
848 {
849  ASSERT (KeGetCurrentIrql () == DISPATCH_LEVEL);
850  ASSERT (OldIrql <= DISPATCH_LEVEL);
851  ASSERT (*SpinLock != 0);
852 
853  InterlockedDecrementRelease (SpinLock);
854  KeLowerIrql (OldIrql);
855 
856  return;
857 }
858 
859 FORCEINLINE
860 LOGICAL
861 ExTryAcquireSpinLockExclusive (
862  IN PEX_SPIN_LOCK SpinLock
863  )
864 {
865  EX_SPIN_LOCK LockContents;
866  EX_SPIN_LOCK NewLockContents;
867 
868  ASSERT (KeGetCurrentIrql () == DISPATCH_LEVEL);
869 
870  do {
871 
872  LockContents = *(volatile EX_SPIN_LOCK *)SpinLock;
873 
874  ASSERT (LockContents != 0);
875 
876  //
877  // If the big pool tag table is already held exclusive, then it cannot
878  // possibly be by the current thread - it must be another thread.
879  // Release our thread's shared reference and inform our caller so
880  // we don't cause the exclusive thread to spin.
881  //
882  // Otherwise it's safe to try to acquire exclusive ourselves.
883  //
884 
885  if (LockContents & EXP_SPIN_LOCK_EXCLUSIVE) {
886  return FALSE;
887  }
888 
889  NewLockContents = (LockContents | EXP_SPIN_LOCK_EXCLUSIVE);
890 
891  if (InterlockedCompareExchangeAcquire (SpinLock,
892  NewLockContents,
893  LockContents) == LockContents) {
894 
895  //
896  // We are the winner of exclusive now. However, we must first
897  // wait for any straggling threads on other processors to release
898  // their references.
899  //
900 
901  while (*(volatile EX_SPIN_LOCK *)SpinLock != (EXP_SPIN_LOCK_EXCLUSIVE | 0x1)) {
902  KeYieldProcessor();
903  NOTHING;
904  }
905 
906  //
907  // Now we finally own the lock exclusively.
908  //
909 
910  return TRUE;
911  }
912 
913  } while (TRUE);
914 }
915 
916 FORCEINLINE
917 KIRQL
918 ExAcquireSpinLockExclusive (
919  IN PEX_SPIN_LOCK SpinLock
920  )
921 {
922  KIRQL OldIrql;
923 
924  do {
925 
926  //
927  // First acquire it shared (so we get a reference).
928  //
929 
930  OldIrql = ExAcquireSpinLockShared (SpinLock);
931 
932  //
933  // Now try to acquire the lock exclusive. If another thread wins,
934  // then we must release and retry.
935  //
936 
937  if (ExTryAcquireSpinLockExclusive (SpinLock) == TRUE) {
938  return OldIrql;
939  }
940 
941  ExReleaseSpinLockShared (SpinLock, OldIrql);
942 
943  KeYieldProcessor();
944 
945  } while (TRUE);
946 }
947 
948 FORCEINLINE
949 VOID
950 ExReleaseSpinLockExclusive (
951  IN PEX_SPIN_LOCK SpinLock,
952  IN KIRQL OldIrql
953  )
954 {
955  ASSERT (KeGetCurrentIrql () == DISPATCH_LEVEL);
956  ASSERT (OldIrql <= DISPATCH_LEVEL);
957  ASSERT (*SpinLock == (EXP_SPIN_LOCK_EXCLUSIVE | 0x1));
958 
959  KeMemoryBarrierWithoutFence();
960  *((EX_SPIN_LOCK volatile *)SpinLock) = 0;
961  KeLowerIrql (OldIrql);
962 
963  return;
964 }
965 
966 #else // (NT_UP)
967 
968 FORCEINLINE
969 KIRQL
970 ExAcquireSpinLockShared (
971  IN PEX_SPIN_LOCK SpinLock
972  )
973 {
974  KIRQL OldIrql;
975 
976  UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER (SpinLock);
977 
978  KeRaiseIrql (DISPATCH_LEVEL, &OldIrql);
979 
980  return OldIrql;
981 }
982 
983 FORCEINLINE
984 KIRQL
985 ExAcquireSpinLockExclusive (
986  IN PEX_SPIN_LOCK SpinLock
987  )
988 {
989  KIRQL OldIrql;
990 
991  UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER (SpinLock);
992 
993  KeRaiseIrql (DISPATCH_LEVEL, &OldIrql);
994 
995  return OldIrql;
996 }
997 
998 FORCEINLINE
999 LOGICAL
1000 ExTryAcquireSpinLockExclusive (
1001  IN PEX_SPIN_LOCK SpinLock
1002  )
1003 {
1004  UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER (SpinLock);
1005 
1006  return TRUE;
1007 }
1008 
1009 FORCEINLINE

1013  IN KIRQL OldIrql
1014  )

1016  UNREFERENCED_PARAMETER (SpinLock);
1017

1019  ASSERT (OldIrql <= DISPATCH_LEVEL);
1020 
1021  KeLowerIrql (OldIrql);
1022 
1023  return;
1024 }

1034

1036  ASSERT (OldIrql <= DISPATCH_LEVEL);
1037 
1038  KeLowerIrql (OldIrql);
1039 
1040  return;
1041 }
1042 
1043 #endif

1296 // end_wdm end_ntddk end_nthal end_ntifs end_ntosp
1297 //
1298 // Define non-blocking interlocked queue functions.
1299 //
1300 // A non-blocking queue is a singly link list of queue entries with a
1301 // head pointer and a tail pointer. The head and tail pointers use
1302 // sequenced pointers as do next links in the entries themselves. The
1303 // queueing discipline is FIFO. New entries are inserted at the tail
1304 // of the list and current entries are removed from the front of the
1305 // list.
1306 //
1307 // Non-blocking queues require a descriptor for each entry in the queue.
1308 // A descriptor consists of a sequenced next pointer and a PVOID data
1309 // value. Descriptors for a queue must be preallocated and inserted in
1310 // an SLIST before calling the function to initialize a non-blocking
1311 // queue header. The SLIST should have as many entries as required for
1312 // the respective queue.
1313 //
1314 
1315 typedef struct _NBQUEUE_BLOCK {
1316  ULONG64 Next;
1317  ULONG64 Data;
1318 } NBQUEUE_BLOCK, *PNBQUEUE_BLOCK;
1319 
1320 PVOID
1321 ExInitializeNBQueueHead (
1322  IN PSLIST_HEADER SlistHead
1323  );
1324 
1325 BOOLEAN
1326 ExInsertTailNBQueue (
1327  IN PVOID Header,
1328  IN ULONG64 Value
1329  );
1330 
1331 BOOLEAN
1332 ExRemoveHeadNBQueue (
1333  IN PVOID Header,
1334  OUT PULONG64 Value
1335  );
1336 
1337 // begin_wdm begin_ntddk begin_nthal begin_ntifs begin_ntosp begin_ntndis
1338 //
1339 // Define interlocked sequenced listhead functions.
1340 //
1341 // A sequenced interlocked list is a singly linked list with a header that
1342 // contains the current depth and a sequence number. Each time an entry is
1343 // inserted or removed from the list the depth is updated and the sequence
1344 // number is incremented. This enables AMD64, IA64, and Pentium and later
1345 // machines to insert and remove from the list without the use of spinlocks.
1346 //
1347 
1348 #if !defined(_WINBASE_)
1349 
1350 /*++
1351 
1352 Routine Description:
1353 
1354  This function initializes a sequenced singly linked listhead.
1355 
1356 Arguments:
1357 
1358  SListHead - Supplies a pointer to a sequenced singly linked listhead.
1359 
1360 Return Value:
1361 
1362  None.
1363 
1364 --*/
1365 
1366 #if defined(_WIN64) && (defined(_NTDRIVER_) || defined(_NTDDK_) || defined(_NTIFS_) || defined(_NTHAL_) || defined(_NTOSP_))
1367 
1368 NTKERNELAPI
1369 VOID
1370 InitializeSListHead (
1371  __out PSLIST_HEADER SListHead
1372  );
1373 
1374 #else
1375 
1376 __inline
1377 VOID
1378 InitializeSListHead (
1379  __out PSLIST_HEADER SListHead
1380  )
1381 
1382 {
1383 
1384 #ifdef _WIN64
1385 
1386  //
1387  // Slist headers must be 16 byte aligned.
1388  //
1389 
1390  if ((ULONG_PTR) SListHead & 0x0f) {
1391 
1392  DbgPrint( "InitializeSListHead unaligned Slist header. Address = %p, Caller = %p\n", SListHead, _ReturnAddress());
1393  RtlRaiseStatus(STATUS_DATATYPE_MISALIGNMENT);
1394  }
1395 
1396 #endif
1397 
1398  SListHead->Alignment = 0;
1399 
1400  return;
1401 }
1402 
1403 #endif
1404 
1405 #endif // !defined(_WINBASE_)
1406 
1407 #define ExInitializeSListHead InitializeSListHead

1697 /*++
1698 
1699 Routine Description:
1700 
1701  This function removes (pops) the first entry from the specified
1702  nonpaged lookaside list.
1703 
1704 Arguments:
1705 
1706  Lookaside - Supplies a pointer to a nonpaged lookaside list structure.
1707 
1708 Return Value:
1709 
1710  If an entry is removed from the specified lookaside list, then the
1711  address of the entry is returned as the function value. Otherwise,
1712  NULL is returned.
1713 
1714 --*/
1715 
1716 {
1717 
1718  PVOID Entry;
1719 
1720  Lookaside->L.TotalAllocates += 1;
1721 
1722 #if defined(_WIN2K_COMPAT_SLIST_USAGE) && defined(_X86_)
1723 
1724  Entry = ExInterlockedPopEntrySList(&Lookaside->L.ListHead,
1725  &Lookaside->Lock__ObsoleteButDoNotDelete);
1726 
1727 
1728 #else
1729 
1730  Entry = InterlockedPopEntrySList(&Lookaside->L.ListHead);
1731 
1732 #endif
1733 
1734  if (Entry == NULL) {
1735  Lookaside->L.AllocateMisses += 1;
1736  Entry = (Lookaside->L.Allocate)(Lookaside->L.Type,
1737  Lookaside->L.Size,
1738  Lookaside->L.Tag);
1739  }
1740 
1741  return Entry;
1742 }

1744 __inline
1745 VOID
1746 ExFreeToNPagedLookasideList(
1747  IN PNPAGED_LOOKASIDE_LIST Lookaside,
1748  IN PVOID Entry
1749  )
1750 
1751 /*++
1752 
1753 Routine Description:
1754 
1755  This function inserts (pushes) the specified entry into the specified
1756  nonpaged lookaside list.
1757 
1758 Arguments:
1759 
1760  Lookaside - Supplies a pointer to a nonpaged lookaside list structure.
1761 
1762  Entry - Supples a pointer to the entry that is inserted in the
1763  lookaside list.
1764 
1765 Return Value:
1766 
1767  None.
1768 
1769 --*/
1770 
1771 {
1772 
1773  Lookaside->L.TotalFrees += 1;
1774  if (ExQueryDepthSList(&Lookaside->L.ListHead) >= Lookaside->L.Depth) {
1775  Lookaside->L.FreeMisses += 1;
1776  (Lookaside->L.Free)(Entry);
1777 
1778  } else {
1779 
1780 #if defined(_WIN2K_COMPAT_SLIST_USAGE) && defined(_X86_)
1781 
1782  ExInterlockedPushEntrySList(&Lookaside->L.ListHead,
1783  (PSLIST_ENTRY)Entry,
1784  &Lookaside->Lock__ObsoleteButDoNotDelete);
1785 
1786 #else
1787 
1788  InterlockedPushEntrySList(&Lookaside->L.ListHead,
1789  (PSLIST_ENTRY)Entry);
1790 
1791 #endif
1792 
1793  }
1794  return;
1795 }

1973 //
1974 // Define per processor nonpage lookaside list structures.
1975 //
1976 
1977 typedef enum _PP_NPAGED_LOOKASIDE_NUMBER {
1978  LookasideSmallIrpList,
1979  LookasideLargeIrpList,
1980  LookasideMdlList,
1981  LookasideCreateInfoList,
1982  LookasideNameBufferList,
1983  LookasideTwilightList,
1984  LookasideCompletionList,
1985  LookasideMaximumList
1986 } PP_NPAGED_LOOKASIDE_NUMBER, *PPP_NPAGED_LOOKASIDE_NUMBER;
1987 
1988 #if !defined(_CROSS_PLATFORM_)
1989 
1990 FORCEINLINE
1991 PVOID
1992 ExAllocateFromPPLookasideList (
1993  IN PP_NPAGED_LOOKASIDE_NUMBER Number
1994  )
1995 
1996 /*++
1997 
1998 Routine Description:
1999 
2000  This function removes (pops) the first entry from the specified per
2001  processor lookaside list.
2002 
2003  N.B. It is possible to context switch during the allocation from a
2004  per processor nonpaged lookaside list, but this should happen
2005  infrequently and should not aversely effect the benefits of
2006  per processor lookaside lists.
2007 
2008 Arguments:
2009 
2010  Number - Supplies the per processor nonpaged lookaside list number.
2011 
2012 Return Value:
2013 
2014  If an entry is removed from the specified lookaside list, then the
2015  address of the entry is returned as the function value. Otherwise,
2016  NULL is returned.
2017 
2018 --*/
2019 
2020 {
2021 
2022  PVOID Entry;
2023  PGENERAL_LOOKASIDE Lookaside;
2024  PKPRCB Prcb;
2025 
2026  ASSERT((Number >= 0) && (Number < LookasideMaximumList));
2027 
2028  //
2029  // Attempt to allocate from the per processor lookaside list.
2030  //
2031 
2032  Prcb = KeGetCurrentPrcb();
2033  Lookaside = Prcb->PPLookasideList[Number].P;
2034  Lookaside->TotalAllocates += 1;
2035  Entry = InterlockedPopEntrySList(&Lookaside->ListHead);
2036 
2037  //
2038  // If the per processor allocation attempt failed, then attempt to
2039  // allocate from the system lookaside list.
2040  //
2041 
2042  if (Entry == NULL) {
2043  Lookaside->AllocateMisses += 1;
2044  Lookaside = Prcb->PPLookasideList[Number].L;
2045  Lookaside->TotalAllocates += 1;
2046  Entry = InterlockedPopEntrySList(&Lookaside->ListHead);
2047  if (Entry == NULL) {
2048  Lookaside->AllocateMisses += 1;
2049  Entry = (Lookaside->Allocate)(Lookaside->Type,
2050  Lookaside->Size,
2051  Lookaside->Tag);
2052  }
2053  }
2054 
2055  return Entry;
2056 }
2057 
2058 FORCEINLINE
2059 VOID
2060 ExFreeToPPLookasideList (
2061  IN PP_NPAGED_LOOKASIDE_NUMBER Number,
2062  IN PVOID Entry
2063  )
2064 
2065 /*++
2066 
2067 Routine Description:
2068 
2069  This function inserts (pushes) the specified entry into the specified
2070  per processor lookaside list.
2071 
2072  N.B. It is possible to context switch during the free of a per
2073  processor nonpaged lookaside list, but this should happen
2074  infrequently and should not aversely effect the benefits of
2075  per processor lookaside lists.
2076 
2077 Arguments:
2078 
2079  Number - Supplies the per processor nonpaged lookaside list number.
2080 
2081  Entry - Supples a pointer to the entry that is inserted in the per
2082  processor lookaside list.
2083 
2084 Return Value:
2085 
2086  None.
2087 
2088 --*/
2089 
2090 {
2091 
2092  PGENERAL_LOOKASIDE Lookaside;
2093  PKPRCB Prcb;
2094 
2095  ASSERT((Number >= 0) && (Number < LookasideMaximumList));
2096 
2097  //
2098  // If the current depth is less than of equal to the maximum depth, then
2099  // free the specified entry to the per processor lookaside list. Otherwise,
2100  // free the entry to the system lookaside list;
2101  //
2102  //
2103 
2104  Prcb = KeGetCurrentPrcb();
2105  Lookaside = Prcb->PPLookasideList[Number].P;
2106  Lookaside->TotalFrees += 1;
2107  if (ExQueryDepthSList(&Lookaside->ListHead) >= Lookaside->Depth) {
2108  Lookaside->FreeMisses += 1;
2109  Lookaside = Prcb->PPLookasideList[Number].L;
2110  Lookaside->TotalFrees += 1;
2111  if (ExQueryDepthSList(&Lookaside->ListHead) >= Lookaside->Depth) {
2112  Lookaside->FreeMisses += 1;
2113  (Lookaside->Free)(Entry);
2114  return;
2115  }
2116  }
2117 
2118  InterlockedPushEntrySList(&Lookaside->ListHead,
2119  (PSLIST_ENTRY)Entry);
2120 
2121  return;
2122 }
2123

2193 ExRaiseDatatypeMisalignment (

2195  );

2200 ExRaiseAccessViolation (
2201  VOID

2205 //
2206 // Probe function definitions
2207 //
2208 // Probe for read functions.
2209 //
2210 //++
2211 //
2212 // VOID
2213 // ProbeForRead (
2214 // IN PVOID Address,
2215 // IN ULONG Length,
2216 // IN ULONG Alignment
2217 // )
2218 //
2219 //--
2220 
2221 #define ProbeForRead(Address, Length, Alignment) { \
2222  ASSERT(((Alignment) == 1) || ((Alignment) == 2) || \
2223  ((Alignment) == 4) || ((Alignment) == 8) || \
2224  ((Alignment) == 16)); \
2225  \
2226  if ((Length) != 0) { \
2227  if (((ULONG_PTR)(Address) & ((Alignment) - 1)) != 0) { \
2228  ExRaiseDatatypeMisalignment(); \
2229  \
2230  } \
2231  if ((((ULONG_PTR)(Address) + (Length)) > (ULONG_PTR)MM_USER_PROBE_ADDRESS) || \
2232  (((ULONG_PTR)(Address) + (Length)) < (ULONG_PTR)(Address))) { \
2233  *(volatile UCHAR * const)MM_USER_PROBE_ADDRESS = 0; \
2234  } \
2235  } \
2236 }
2237 
2238 #if defined(_AMD64_)
2239 
2240 FORCEINLINE
2241 VOID
2242 ProbeForReadSmallStructure (
2243  IN PVOID Address,
2244  IN SIZE_T Size,
2245  IN ULONG Alignment
2246  )
2247 
2248 /*++
2249 
2250 Routine Description:
2251 
2252  Probes a structure for read access whose size is known at compile time.
2253 
2254  N.B. A NULL structure address is not allowed.
2255 
2256 Arguments:
2257 
2258  Address - Supples a pointer to the structure.
2259 
2260  Size - Supplies the size of the structure.
2261 
2262  Alignment - Supplies the alignment of structure.
2263 
2264 Return Value:
2265 
2266  None
2267 
2268 --*/
2269 
2270 {
2271 
2272  ASSERT((Alignment == 1) || (Alignment == 2) ||
2273  (Alignment == 4) || (Alignment == 8) ||
2274  (Alignment == 16));
2275 
2276  if ((Size == 0) || (Size >= 0x10000)) {
2277 
2278  ASSERT(0);
2279 
2280  ProbeForRead(Address, Size, Alignment);
2281 
2282  } else {
2283  if (((ULONG_PTR)Address & (Alignment - 1)) != 0) {
2284  ExRaiseDatatypeMisalignment();
2285  }
2286 
2287  if ((PUCHAR)Address >= (UCHAR * const)MM_USER_PROBE_ADDRESS) {
2288  Address = (UCHAR * const)MM_USER_PROBE_ADDRESS;
2289  }
2290 
2291  _ReadWriteBarrier();
2292  *(volatile UCHAR *)Address;
2293  }
2294 }
2295 
2296 #else
2297 
2298 #define ProbeForReadSmallStructure(Address, Size, Alignment) { \
2299  ASSERT(((Alignment) == 1) || ((Alignment) == 2) || \
2300  ((Alignment) == 4) || ((Alignment) == 8) || \
2301  ((Alignment) == 16)); \
2302  if ((Size == 0) || (Size > 0x10000)) { \
2303  ASSERT(0); \
2304  ProbeForRead(Address, Size, Alignment); \
2305  } else { \
2306  if (((ULONG_PTR)(Address) & ((Alignment) - 1)) != 0) { \
2307  ExRaiseDatatypeMisalignment(); \
2308  } \
2309  if ((ULONG_PTR)(Address) >= (ULONG_PTR)MM_USER_PROBE_ADDRESS) { \
2310  *(volatile UCHAR * const)MM_USER_PROBE_ADDRESS = 0; \
2311  } \
2312  } \
2313 }

4214 // number of worker threads processing items in this queue. These two
4215 // pieces of information need to do a RMW together, so it's simpler to
4216 // smush them together than to use a lock.
4217 //

4223 
4224  ULONG QueueDisabled : 1;

4226  //
4227  // MakeThreadsAsNecessary indicates whether this work queue is eligible
4228  // for dynamic creation of threads not just for deadlock detection,
4229  // but to ensure that the CPUs are all kept busy clearing any work
4230  // item backlog.
4231  //
4232 
4233  ULONG MakeThreadsAsNecessary : 1;
4234 
4235  ULONG WaitMode : 1;
4236 
4237  ULONG WorkerCount : 29;
4238  };
4239  LONG QueueWorkerInfo;
4240 } EX_QUEUE_WORKER_INFO;

4333 //++
4334 //
4335 // PVOID
4336 // ExAllocateFromZone(
4337 // IN PZONE_HEADER Zone
4338 // )
4339 //
4340 // Routine Description:
4341 //
4342 // This routine removes an entry from the zone and returns a pointer to it.
4343 //
4344 // Arguments:
4345 //
4346 // Zone - Pointer to the zone header controlling the storage from which the
4347 // entry is to be allocated.
4348 //
4349 // Return Value:
4350 //
4351 // The function value is a pointer to the storage allocated from the zone.
4352 //
4353 //--
4354 #if PRAGMA_DEPRECATED_DDK
4355 #pragma deprecated(ExAllocateFromZone)
4356 #endif
4357 #define ExAllocateFromZone(Zone) \
4358  (PVOID)((Zone)->FreeList.Next); \
4359  if ( (Zone)->FreeList.Next ) (Zone)->FreeList.Next = (Zone)->FreeList.Next->Next
4360 
4361 
4362 //++
4363 //
4364 // PVOID
4365 // ExFreeToZone(
4366 // IN PZONE_HEADER Zone,
4367 // IN PVOID Block
4368 // )
4369 //
4370 // Routine Description:
4371 //
4372 // This routine places the specified block of storage back onto the free
4373 // list in the specified zone.
4374 //
4375 // Arguments:
4376 //
4377 // Zone - Pointer to the zone header controlling the storage to which the
4378 // entry is to be inserted.
4379 //
4380 // Block - Pointer to the block of storage to be freed back to the zone.
4381 //
4382 // Return Value:
4383 //
4384 // Pointer to previous block of storage that was at the head of the free
4385 // list. NULL implies the zone went from no available free blocks to
4386 // at least one free block.
4387 //
4388 //--
4389 
4390 #if PRAGMA_DEPRECATED_DDK
4391 #pragma deprecated(ExFreeToZone)
4392 #endif
4393 #define ExFreeToZone(Zone,Block) \
4394  ( ((PSINGLE_LIST_ENTRY)(Block))->Next = (Zone)->FreeList.Next, \
4395  (Zone)->FreeList.Next = ((PSINGLE_LIST_ENTRY)(Block)), \
4396  ((PSINGLE_LIST_ENTRY)(Block))->Next \
4397  )
4398 
4399 //++
4400 //
4401 // BOOLEAN
4402 // ExIsFullZone(
4403 // IN PZONE_HEADER Zone
4404 // )
4405 //
4406 // Routine Description:
4407 //
4408 // This routine determines if the specified zone is full or not. A zone
4409 // is considered full if the free list is empty.
4410 //
4411 // Arguments:
4412 //
4413 // Zone - Pointer to the zone header to be tested.
4414 //
4415 // Return Value:
4416 //
4417 // TRUE if the zone is full and FALSE otherwise.
4418 //
4419 //--
4420 
4421 #if PRAGMA_DEPRECATED_DDK
4422 #pragma deprecated(ExIsFullZone)
4423 #endif
4424 #define ExIsFullZone(Zone) \
4425  ( (Zone)->FreeList.Next == (PSINGLE_LIST_ENTRY)NULL )
4426 
4427 //++
4428 //
4429 // PVOID
4430 // ExInterlockedAllocateFromZone(
4431 // IN PZONE_HEADER Zone,
4432 // IN PKSPIN_LOCK Lock
4433 // )
4434 //
4435 // Routine Description:
4436 //
4437 // This routine removes an entry from the zone and returns a pointer to it.
4438 // The removal is performed with the specified lock owned for the sequence
4439 // to make it MP-safe.
4440 //
4441 // Arguments:
4442 //
4443 // Zone - Pointer to the zone header controlling the storage from which the
4444 // entry is to be allocated.
4445 //
4446 // Lock - Pointer to the spin lock which should be obtained before removing
4447 // the entry from the allocation list. The lock is released before
4448 // returning to the caller.
4449 //
4450 // Return Value:
4451 //
4452 // The function value is a pointer to the storage allocated from the zone.
4453 //
4454 //--
4455 
4456 #if PRAGMA_DEPRECATED_DDK
4457 #pragma deprecated(ExInterlockedAllocateFromZone)
4458 #endif
4459 #define ExInterlockedAllocateFromZone(Zone,Lock) \
4460  (PVOID) ExInterlockedPopEntryList( &(Zone)->FreeList, Lock )
4461 
4462 //++
4463 //
4464 // PVOID
4465 // ExInterlockedFreeToZone(
4466 // IN PZONE_HEADER Zone,
4467 // IN PVOID Block,
4468 // IN PKSPIN_LOCK Lock
4469 // )
4470 //
4471 // Routine Description:
4472 //
4473 // This routine places the specified block of storage back onto the free
4474 // list in the specified zone. The insertion is performed with the lock
4475 // owned for the sequence to make it MP-safe.
4476 //
4477 // Arguments:
4478 //
4479 // Zone - Pointer to the zone header controlling the storage to which the
4480 // entry is to be inserted.
4481 //
4482 // Block - Pointer to the block of storage to be freed back to the zone.
4483 //
4484 // Lock - Pointer to the spin lock which should be obtained before inserting
4485 // the entry onto the free list. The lock is released before returning
4486 // to the caller.
4487 //
4488 // Return Value:
4489 //
4490 // Pointer to previous block of storage that was at the head of the free
4491 // list. NULL implies the zone went from no available free blocks to
4492 // at least one free block.
4493 //
4494 //--
4495 
4496 #if PRAGMA_DEPRECATED_DDK
4497 #pragma deprecated(ExInterlockedFreeToZone)
4498 #endif
4499 #define ExInterlockedFreeToZone(Zone,Block,Lock) \
4500  ExInterlockedPushEntryList( &(Zone)->FreeList, ((PSINGLE_LIST_ENTRY) (Block)), Lock )

4824 //
4825 // Push lock definitions
4826 //
4827 typedef struct _EX_PUSH_LOCK {
4828 
4829 //
4830 // LOCK bit is set for both exclusive and shared acquires
4831 //
4832 #define EX_PUSH_LOCK_LOCK_V ((ULONG_PTR)0x0)
4833 #define EX_PUSH_LOCK_LOCK ((ULONG_PTR)0x1)
4834 
4835 //
4836 // Waiting bit designates that the pointer has chained waiters
4837 //
4838 
4839 #define EX_PUSH_LOCK_WAITING ((ULONG_PTR)0x2)
4840 
4841 //
4842 // Waking bit designates that we are either traversing the list
4843 // to wake threads or optimizing the list
4844 //
4845 
4846 #define EX_PUSH_LOCK_WAKING ((ULONG_PTR)0x4)
4847 
4848 //
4849 // Set if the lock is held shared by multiple owners and there are waiters
4850 //
4851 
4852 #define EX_PUSH_LOCK_MULTIPLE_SHARED ((ULONG_PTR)0x8)
4853 
4854 //
4855 // Total shared Acquires are incremented using this
4856 //
4857 #define EX_PUSH_LOCK_SHARE_INC ((ULONG_PTR)0x10)
4858 #define EX_PUSH_LOCK_PTR_BITS ((ULONG_PTR)0xf)
4859 
4860  union {
4861  struct {
4862  ULONG_PTR Locked : 1;
4863  ULONG_PTR Waiting : 1;
4864  ULONG_PTR Waking : 1;
4865  ULONG_PTR MultipleShared : 1;
4866  ULONG_PTR Shared : sizeof (ULONG_PTR) * 8 - 4;
4867  };
4868  ULONG_PTR Value;
4869  PVOID Ptr;
4870  };
4871 } EX_PUSH_LOCK, *PEX_PUSH_LOCK;

4879 #endif

4939  //

4941  ULONG RunRefSize;
4942 
4943  //
4944  // Indicates # of entries in the array of rundown ref structures
4945  //
4946 
4947  ULONG Number;
4948 } EX_RUNDOWN_REF_CACHE_AWARE, *PEX_RUNDOWN_REF_CACHE_AWARE;
4949 
4950 
4951 
4952 //
4953 // The Ex/Ob handle table interface package (in handle.c)
4954 //
4955 
4956 //
4957 // The Ex/Ob handle table package uses a common handle definition. The actual
4958 // type definition for a handle is a pvoid and is declared in sdk/inc. This
4959 // package uses only the low 32 bits of the pvoid pointer.
4960 //
4961 // For simplicity we declare a new typedef called an exhandle
4962 //
4963 // The 2 bits of an EXHANDLE is available to the application and is
4964 // ignored by the system. The next 24 bits store the handle table entry
4965 // index and is used to refer to a particular entry in a handle table.
4966 //
4967 // Note that this format is immutable because there are outside programs with
4968 // hardwired code that already assumes the format of a handle.
4969 //
4970 
4971 typedef struct _EXHANDLE {
4972 
4973  union {
4974 
4975  struct {
4976 
4977  //
4978  // Application available tag bits
4979  //
4980 
4981  ULONG TagBits : 2;
4982 
4983  //
4984  // The handle table entry index
4985  //
4986 
4987  ULONG Index : 30;
4988 
4989  };
4990 
4991  HANDLE GenericHandleOverlay;
4992 
4993 #define HANDLE_VALUE_INC 4 // Amount to increment the Value to get to the next handle
4994 
4995  ULONG_PTR Value;
4996  };
4997 
4998 } EXHANDLE, *PEXHANDLE;
4999 // end_ntosp
5000 
5001 typedef struct _HANDLE_TABLE_ENTRY_INFO {
5002 
5003 
5004  //
5005  // The following field contains the audit mask for the handle if one
5006  // exists. The purpose of the audit mask is to record all of the accesses
5007  // that may have been audited when the handle was opened in order to
5008  // support "per operation" based auditing. It is computed by walking the
5009  // SACL of the object being opened and keeping a record of all of the audit
5010  // ACEs that apply to the open operation going on. Each set bit corresponds
5011  // to an access that would be audited. As each operation takes place, its
5012  // corresponding access bit is removed from this mask.
5013  //
5014 
5015  ACCESS_MASK AuditMask;
5016 
5017 } HANDLE_TABLE_ENTRY_INFO, *PHANDLE_TABLE_ENTRY_INFO;
5018 
5019 //
5020 // A handle table stores multiple handle table entries, each entry is looked
5021 // up by its exhandle. A handle table entry has really two fields.
5022 //
5023 // The first field contains a pointer object and is overloaded with the three
5024 // low order bits used by ob to denote inherited, protected, and audited
5025 // objects. The upper bit used as a handle table entry lock. Note, this
5026 // means that all valid object pointers must be at least longword aligned and
5027 // have their sign bit set (i.e., be negative).
5028 //
5029 // The next field contains the access mask (sometimes in the form of a granted
5030 // access index, and creator callback trace) if the entry is in use or a
5031 // pointer in the free list if the entry is free.
5032 //
5033 // Two things to note:
5034 //
5035 // 1. An entry is free if the object pointer is null, this means that the
5036 // following field contains the FreeTableEntryList.
5037 //
5038 // 2. An entry is unlocked if the object pointer is positive and locked if its
5039 // negative. The handle package through callbacks and Map Handle to
5040 // Pointer will lock the entry (thus making the pointer valid) outside
5041 // routines can then read and reset the attributes field and the object
5042 // provided they don't unlock the entry. When the callbacks return the
5043 // entry will be unlocked and the callers or MapHandleToPointer will need
5044 // to call UnlockHandleTableEntry explicitly.
5045 //
5046 
5047 typedef struct _HANDLE_TABLE_ENTRY {
5048 
5049  //
5050  // The pointer to the object overloaded with three ob attributes bits in
5051  // the lower order and the high bit to denote locked or unlocked entries
5052  //
5053 
5054  union {
5055 
5056  PVOID Object;
5057 
5058  ULONG ObAttributes;
5059 
5060  PHANDLE_TABLE_ENTRY_INFO InfoTable;
5061 
5062  ULONG_PTR Value;
5063  };
5064 
5065  //
5066  // This field either contains the granted access mask for the handle or an
5067  // ob variation that also stores the same information. Or in the case of
5068  // a free entry the field stores the index for the next free entry in the
5069  // free list. This is like a FAT chain, and is used instead of pointers
5070  // to make table duplication easier, because the entries can just be
5071  // copied without needing to modify pointers.
5072  //
5073 
5074  union {
5075 
5076  union {
5077 
5078  ACCESS_MASK GrantedAccess;
5079 
5080  struct {
5081 
5082  USHORT GrantedAccessIndex;
5083  USHORT CreatorBackTraceIndex;
5084  };
5085  };
5086 
5087  LONG NextFreeTableEntry;
5088  };
5089 
5090 } HANDLE_TABLE_ENTRY, *PHANDLE_TABLE_ENTRY;
5091 
5092 
5093 //
5094 // Define a structure to track handle usage
5095 //
5096 
5097 #define HANDLE_TRACE_DB_MAX_STACKS 65536
5098 #define HANDLE_TRACE_DB_MIN_STACKS 128
5099 #define HANDLE_TRACE_DB_DEFAULT_STACKS 4096
5100 #define HANDLE_TRACE_DB_STACK_SIZE 16
5101 
5102 typedef struct _HANDLE_TRACE_DB_ENTRY {
5103  CLIENT_ID ClientId;
5104  HANDLE Handle;
5105 #define HANDLE_TRACE_DB_OPEN 1
5106 #define HANDLE_TRACE_DB_CLOSE 2
5107 #define HANDLE_TRACE_DB_BADREF 3
5108  ULONG Type;
5109  PVOID StackTrace[HANDLE_TRACE_DB_STACK_SIZE];
5110 } HANDLE_TRACE_DB_ENTRY, *PHANDLE_TRACE_DB_ENTRY;

5119  //

5175 // global list. This list is used by the snapshot handle tables call.
5176 //
5177

5182  // A pointer to the top level handle table tree node.
5183  //

5186

5194 
5195

5197  // These locks are used for table expansion and preventing the A-B-A problem
5198  // on handle allocate.
5199  //
5200 
5201 #define HANDLE_TABLE_LOCKS 4
5202 
5203  EX_PUSH_LOCK HandleTableLock[HANDLE_TABLE_LOCKS];
5204

5207  // lock.
5208  //

5210  LIST_ENTRY HandleTableList;
5211

5213  // Define a field to block on if a handle is found locked.
5214  //

5216

5218  // Debug info. Only allocated if we are debugging handles
5219  //
5220  PHANDLE_TRACE_DEBUG_INFO DebugInfo;
5221 
5222  //
5223  // The number of pages for additional info.
5224  // This counter is used to improve the performance
5225  // in ExGetHandleInfo
5226  //
5227  LONG ExtraInfoPages;
5228 
5229  //
5230  // This is a singly linked list of free table entries. We don't actually
5231  // use pointers, but have each store the index of the next free entry
5232  // in the list. The list is managed as a lifo list. We also keep track
5233  // of the next index that we have to allocate pool to hold.
5234  //
5235 
5236  ULONG FirstFree;
5237 
5238  //
5239  // We free handles to this list when handle debugging is on or if we see
5240  // that a thread has this handles bucket lock held. The allows us to delay reuse
5241  // of handles to get a better chance of catching offenders
5242  //
5243 
5244  ULONG LastFree;
5245 
5246  //
5247  // This is the next handle index needing a pool allocation. Its also used as a bound
5248  // for good handles.
5249  //
5250 
5251  ULONG NextHandleNeedingPool;
5252 
5253  //
5254  // The number of handle table entries in use.
5255  //
5256 
5257  LONG HandleCount;
5258 
5259  //
5260  // Define a flags field
5261  //
5262  union {
5263  ULONG Flags;
5264 
5265  //
5266  // For optimization we reuse handle values quickly. This can be a problem for
5267  // some usages of handles and makes debugging a little harder. If this
5268  // bit is set then we always use FIFO handle allocation.
5269  //
5270  BOOLEAN StrictFIFO : 1;
5271  };
5272 
5273 } HANDLE_TABLE, *PHANDLE_TABLE;

5534 //
5535 // Locally Unique Identifier Services
5536 //
5537 
5538 NTKERNELAPI
5539 BOOLEAN
5540 ExLuidInitialization (
5541  VOID
5542  );
5543 
5544 //
5545 // VOID
5546 // ExAllocateLocallyUniqueId (
5547 // PLUID Luid
5548 // )
5549 //
5550 //*++
5551 //
5552 // Routine Description:
5553 //
5554 // This function returns an LUID value that is unique since the system
5555 // was last rebooted. It is unique only on the system it is generated on
5556 // and not network wide.
5557 //
5558 // N.B. A LUID is a 64-bit value and for all practical purposes will
5559 // never carry in the lifetime of a single boot of the system.
5560 // At an increment rate of 1ns, the value would carry to zero in
5561 // approximately 126 years.
5562 //
5563 // Arguments:
5564 //
5565 // Luid - Supplies a pointer to a variable that receives the allocated
5566 // locally unique Id.
5567 //
5568 // Return Value:
5569 //
5570 // The allocated LUID value.
5571 //
5572 // --*/
5573 
5574 
5575 extern LARGE_INTEGER ExpLuid;
5576 extern const LARGE_INTEGER ExpLuidIncrement;
5577 
5578 __inline
5579 VOID
5580 ExAllocateLocallyUniqueId (
5581  IN OUT PLUID Luid
5582  )
5583 
5584 {
5585  LARGE_INTEGER Initial;
5586 
5587 #if defined (_WIN64) && !defined(_X86AMD64_)
5588  Initial.QuadPart = InterlockedAdd64 (&ExpLuid.QuadPart, ExpLuidIncrement.QuadPart);
5589 #else
5590  LARGE_INTEGER Value;
5591 
5592 
5593  while (1) {
5594  Initial.QuadPart = ExpLuid.QuadPart;
5595 
5596  Value.QuadPart = Initial.QuadPart + ExpLuidIncrement.QuadPart;
5597  Value.QuadPart = InterlockedCompareExchange64(&ExpLuid.QuadPart,
5598  Value.QuadPart,
5599  Initial.QuadPart);
5600  if (Initial.QuadPart != Value.QuadPart) {
5601  continue;
5602  }
5603  break;
5604  }
5605 
5606 #endif
5607 
5608  Luid->LowPart = Initial.LowPart;
5609  Luid->HighPart = Initial.HighPart;
5610  return;
5611 }

5620 ExGetPreviousMode(

5631 NTAPI

5633  __in PEXCEPTION_RECORD ExceptionRecord

5635 
5636 // begin_ntosp
5637 
5638 FORCEINLINE
5639 VOID
5640 ProbeForWriteSmallStructure (
5641  IN PVOID Address,
5642  IN SIZE_T Size,
5643  IN ULONG Alignment
5644  )
5645 
5646 /*++
5647 
5648 Routine Description:
5649 
5650  Probes a structure for write access whose size is known at compile time.
5651 
5652 Arguments:
5653 
5654  Address - Supples a pointer to the structure.
5655 
5656  Size - Supplies the size of the structure.
5657 
5658  Alignment - Supplies the alignment of structure.
5659 
5660 Return Value:
5661 
5662  None
5663 
5664 --*/
5665 
5666 {
5667 
5668  ASSERT((Alignment == 1) || (Alignment == 2) ||
5669  (Alignment == 4) || (Alignment == 8) ||
5670  (Alignment == 16));
5671 
5672  //
5673  // If the size of the structure is > 4k then call the standard routine.
5674  // wow64 uses a page size of 4k even on ia64.
5675  //
5676 
5677  if ((Size == 0) || (Size >= 0x1000)) {
5678 
5679  ASSERT(0);
5680 
5681  ProbeForWrite(Address, Size, Alignment);
5682 
5683  } else {
5684  if (((ULONG_PTR)(Address) & (Alignment - 1)) != 0) {
5685  ExRaiseDatatypeMisalignment();
5686  }
5687 
5688 #if defined(_AMD64_)
5689 
5690  if ((ULONG_PTR)(Address) >= (ULONG_PTR)MM_USER_PROBE_ADDRESS) {
5691  Address = (UCHAR * const)MM_USER_PROBE_ADDRESS;
5692  }
5693 
5694  ((volatile UCHAR *)(Address))[0] = ((volatile UCHAR *)(Address))[0];
5695  ((volatile UCHAR *)(Address))[Size - 1] = ((volatile UCHAR *)(Address))[Size - 1];
5696 
5697 #else
5698 
5699  if ((ULONG_PTR)(Address) >= (ULONG_PTR)MM_USER_PROBE_ADDRESS) {
5700  *((volatile UCHAR * const)MM_USER_PROBE_ADDRESS) = 0;
5701  }
5702 
5703  *(volatile UCHAR *)(Address) = *(volatile UCHAR *)(Address);
5704  if (Size > Alignment) {
5705  ((volatile UCHAR *)(Address))[(Size - 1) & ~(SIZE_T)(Alignment - 1)] =
5706  ((volatile UCHAR *)(Address))[(Size - 1) & ~(SIZE_T)(Alignment - 1)];
5707  }
5708 
5709 #endif
5710 
5711  }
5712 }
5713

6178 NTKERNELAPI
6179 VOID
6180 FORCEINLINE
6181 FASTCALL
6182 ExInitializeRundownProtection (
6183  __out PEX_RUNDOWN_REF RunRef
6184  )
6185 /*++
6186 
6187 Routine Description:
6188 
6189  Initialize rundown protection structure
6190 
6191 Arguments:
6192 
6193  RunRef - Rundown block to be referenced
6194 
6195 Return Value:
6196 
6197  None
6198 
6199 --*/
6200 {
6201  RunRef->Count = 0;
6202 }
6203 
6204 //
6205 // Reset a rundown protection block
6206 //
6207 
6208 NTKERNELAPI
6209 VOID
6210 FASTCALL
6211 ExfReInitializeRundownProtection (
6212  __out PEX_RUNDOWN_REF RunRef
6213  );
6214 
6215 NTKERNELAPI
6216 VOID
6217 FORCEINLINE
6218 FASTCALL
6219 ExReInitializeRundownProtection (
6220  __out PEX_RUNDOWN_REF RunRef
6221  )
6222 /*++
6223 
6224 Routine Description:
6225 
6226  Reinitialize rundown protection structure after its been rundown
6227 
6228 Arguments:
6229 
6230  RunRef - Rundown block to be referenced
6231 
6232 Return Value:
6233 
6234  None
6235 
6236 --*/
6237 {
6238  PAGED_CODE ();
6239 
6240  ASSERT ((RunRef->Count&EX_RUNDOWN_ACTIVE) != 0);
6241  InterlockedExchangePointer (&RunRef->Ptr, NULL);
6242 }
6243 
6244 
6245 //
6246 // Acquire rundown protection
6247 //
6248 
6249 NTKERNELAPI
6250 BOOLEAN
6251 FASTCALL
6252 ExfAcquireRundownProtection (
6253  __inout PEX_RUNDOWN_REF RunRef
6254  );
6255 
6256 NTKERNELAPI
6257 BOOLEAN
6258 FORCEINLINE
6259 FASTCALL
6260 ExAcquireRundownProtection (
6261  __inout PEX_RUNDOWN_REF RunRef
6262  )
6263 {
6264  ULONG_PTR Value, NewValue;
6265 
6266  Value = ReadForWriteAccess(&RunRef->Count) & ~EX_RUNDOWN_ACTIVE;
6267  NewValue = Value + EX_RUNDOWN_COUNT_INC;
6268  NewValue = (ULONG_PTR) InterlockedCompareExchangePointerAcquire (&RunRef->Ptr,
6269  (PVOID) NewValue,
6270  (PVOID) Value);
6271  if (NewValue == Value) {
6272  return TRUE;
6273  } else {
6274  return ExfAcquireRundownProtection (RunRef);
6275  }
6276 }
6277 
6278 //
6279 // Release rundown protection
6280 //
6281 NTKERNELAPI
6282 VOID
6283 FASTCALL
6284 ExfReleaseRundownProtection (
6285  __inout PEX_RUNDOWN_REF RunRef
6286  );
6287 
6288 NTKERNELAPI
6289 VOID
6290 FORCEINLINE
6291 FASTCALL
6292 ExReleaseRundownProtection (
6293  __inout PEX_RUNDOWN_REF RunRef
6294  )
6295 {
6296  ULONG_PTR Value, NewValue;
6297 
6298  Value = ReadForWriteAccess(&RunRef->Count) & ~EX_RUNDOWN_ACTIVE;
6299  NewValue = Value - EX_RUNDOWN_COUNT_INC;
6300  NewValue = (ULONG_PTR) InterlockedCompareExchangePointerRelease (&RunRef->Ptr,
6301  (PVOID) NewValue,
6302  (PVOID) Value);
6303  if (NewValue != Value) {
6304  ExfReleaseRundownProtection (RunRef);
6305  } else {
6306 
6307  //
6308  // For cache-aware rundown protection it is possible,
6309  // that the value is zero at this point for this processor
6310  //
6311 
6312  ASSERT ((Value >= EX_RUNDOWN_COUNT_INC) || (KeNumberProcessors > 1));
6313  }
6314 }
6315 
6316 //
6317 // Mark rundown block as rundown having been completed.
6318 //
6319 
6320 NTKERNELAPI
6321 VOID
6322 FASTCALL
6323 ExfRundownCompleted (
6324  __out PEX_RUNDOWN_REF RunRef
6325  );
6326 
6327 NTKERNELAPI
6328 VOID
6329 FORCEINLINE
6330 FASTCALL
6331 ExRundownCompleted (
6332  __out PEX_RUNDOWN_REF RunRef
6333  )
6334 /*++
6335 Routine Description:
6336 
6337  Mark rundown block has having completed rundown so we can wait again safely.
6338 
6339 Arguments:
6340 
6341  RunRef - Rundown block to be referenced
6342 
6343 Return Value:
6344 
6345  None
6346 --*/
6347 {
6348  PAGED_CODE ();
6349 
6350  ASSERT ((RunRef->Count&EX_RUNDOWN_ACTIVE) != 0);
6351  InterlockedExchangePointer (&RunRef->Ptr, (PVOID) EX_RUNDOWN_ACTIVE);
6352 }
6353 
6354 //
6355 // Wait for all protected acquires to exit
6356 //
6357 NTKERNELAPI
6358 VOID
6359 FASTCALL
6360 ExfWaitForRundownProtectionRelease (
6361  __inout PEX_RUNDOWN_REF RunRef
6362  );
6363 
6364 NTKERNELAPI
6365 VOID
6366 FORCEINLINE
6367 FASTCALL
6368 ExWaitForRundownProtectionRelease (
6369  __inout PEX_RUNDOWN_REF RunRef
6370  )
6371 {
6372  ULONG_PTR OldValue;
6373 
6374  OldValue = (ULONG_PTR) InterlockedCompareExchangePointerAcquire (&RunRef->Ptr,
6375  (PVOID) EX_RUNDOWN_ACTIVE,
6376  (PVOID) 0);
6377  if (OldValue != 0 && OldValue != EX_RUNDOWN_ACTIVE) {
6378  ExfWaitForRundownProtectionRelease (RunRef);
6379  }
6380 }

6382 //
6383 // Fast reference routines. See ntos\ob\fastref.c for algorithm description.
6384 //
6385 #if defined (_WIN64)
6386 #define MAX_FAST_REFS 15
6387 #else
6388 #define MAX_FAST_REFS 7
6389 #endif
6390 
6391 typedef struct _EX_FAST_REF {
6392  union {
6393  PVOID Object;
6394 #if defined (_WIN64)
6395  ULONG_PTR RefCnt : 4;
6396 #else
6397  ULONG_PTR RefCnt : 3;
6398 #endif
6399  ULONG_PTR Value;
6400  };
6401 } EX_FAST_REF, *PEX_FAST_REF;
6402 
6403 
6404 NTKERNELAPI
6405 LOGICAL
6406 FORCEINLINE
6407 ExFastRefCanBeReferenced (
6408  __in EX_FAST_REF FastRef
6409  )
6410 /*++
6411 
6412 Routine Description:
6413 
6414  This routine allows the caller to determine if the fast reference
6415  structure contains cached references.
6416 
6417 Arguments:
6418 
6419  FastRef - Fast reference block to be used
6420 
6421 Return Value:
6422 
6423  LOGICAL - TRUE: There were cached references in the object,
6424  FALSE: No cached references are available.
6425 
6426 --*/
6427 {
6428  return FastRef.RefCnt != 0;
6429 }
6430 
6431 NTKERNELAPI
6432 LOGICAL
6433 FORCEINLINE
6434 ExFastRefCanBeDereferenced (
6435  __in EX_FAST_REF FastRef
6436  )
6437 /*++
6438 
6439 Routine Description:
6440 
6441  This routine allows the caller to determine if the fast reference
6442  structure contains room for cached references.
6443 
6444 Arguments:
6445 
6446  FastRef - Fast reference block to be used
6447 
6448 Return Value:
6449 
6450  LOGICAL - TRUE: There is space for cached references in the object,
6451  FALSE: No space was available.
6452 
6453 --*/
6454 {
6455  return FastRef.RefCnt != MAX_FAST_REFS;
6456 }

6538 NTKERNELAPI
6539 BOOLEAN
6540 FORCEINLINE
6541 ExFastRefEqualObjects (

6543  __in PVOID Object
6544  )
6545 /*++

6547 Routine Description:
6548

6550  the specified object
6551 
6552 Arguments:

6560 --*/
6561 {
6562  return (BOOLEAN)((FastRef.Value^(ULONG_PTR)Object) <= MAX_FAST_REFS);
6563 }

6598  __in_opt PVOID Object
6599  )
6600 /*++
6601 
6602 Routine Description:
6603 
6604  This routine initializes fast reference structure.
6605 
6606 Arguments:
6607 
6608  FastRef - Fast reference block to be used
6609  Object - Object pointer to be assigned to the fast reference
6610

6615 --*/

6618

6620  FastRef->Object = NULL;
6621  } else {
6622  FastRef->Value = (ULONG_PTR) Object | MAX_FAST_REFS;
6623  }

6626 NTKERNELAPI
6627 VOID
6628 FORCEINLINE
6629 ExFastRefInitializeEx (
6630  __out PEX_FAST_REF FastRef,
6631  __in_opt PVOID Object,
6632  __in ULONG AdditionalRefs
6633  )
6634 /*++
6635

6637 
6638  This routine initializes fast reference structure with the specified additional references.
6639 
6640 Arguments:
6641

6643  Object - Object pointer to be assigned to the fast reference

6654

6672 
6673 
6674 NTKERNELAPI
6675 EX_FAST_REF
6676 FORCEINLINE
6677 ExFastReference (
6678  __inout PEX_FAST_REF FastRef
6679  )
6680 /*++
6681 
6682 Routine Description:
6683 
6684  This routine attempts to obtain a fast (cached) reference from a fast
6685  reference structure.
6686 
6687 Arguments:
6688 
6689  FastRef - Fast reference block to be used
6690 
6691 Return Value:
6692 
6693  EX_FAST_REF - The old or current contents of the fast reference structure.
6694 
6695 --*/
6696 {
6697  EX_FAST_REF OldRef, NewRef;
6698 
6699  while (1) {
6700  //
6701  // Fetch the old contents of the fast ref structure
6702  //
6703  OldRef = ReadForWriteAccess(FastRef);
6704  //
6705  // If the object pointer is null or if there are no cached references
6706  // left then bail. In the second case this reference will need to be
6707  // taken while holding the lock. Both cases are covered by the single
6708  // test of the lower bits since a null pointer can never have cached
6709  // refs.
6710  //
6711  if (OldRef.RefCnt != 0) {
6712  //
6713  // We know the bottom bits can't underflow into the pointer for a
6714  // request that works so just decrement
6715  //
6716  NewRef.Value = OldRef.Value - 1;
6717  NewRef.Object = InterlockedCompareExchangePointerAcquire (&FastRef->Object,
6718  NewRef.Object,
6719  OldRef.Object);
6720  if (NewRef.Object != OldRef.Object) {
6721  //
6722  // The structured changed beneath us. Try the operation again
6723  //
6724  continue;
6725  }
6726  }
6727  break;
6728  }
6729 
6730  return OldRef;
6731 }
6732 
6733 NTKERNELAPI
6734 LOGICAL
6735 FORCEINLINE
6736 ExFastRefDereference (
6737  __inout PEX_FAST_REF FastRef,
6738  __in PVOID Object
6739  )
6740 /*++
6741 
6742 Routine Description:
6743 
6744  This routine attempts to release a fast reference from a fast ref
6745  structure. This routine could be called for a reference obtained
6746  directly from the object but presumably the chances of the pointer
6747  matching would be unlikely. The algorithm will work correctly in this
6748  case.
6749 
6750 Arguments:
6751 
6752  FastRef - Fast reference block to be used
6753 
6754  Object - The original object that the reference was taken on.
6755 
6756 Return Value:
6757 
6758  LOGICAL - TRUE: The fast dereference worked ok, FALSE: the
6759  dereference didn't.
6760 
6761 --*/
6762 {
6763  EX_FAST_REF OldRef, NewRef;
6764 
6765  ASSERT ((((ULONG_PTR)Object)&MAX_FAST_REFS) == 0);
6766  ASSERT (Object != NULL);
6767 
6768  while (1) {
6769  //
6770  // Fetch the old contents of the fast ref structure
6771  //
6772  OldRef = ReadForWriteAccess(FastRef);
6773 
6774  //
6775  // If the reference cache is fully populated or the pointer has
6776  // changed to another object then just return the old value. The
6777  // caller can return the reference to the object instead.
6778  //
6779  if ((OldRef.Value^(ULONG_PTR)Object) >= MAX_FAST_REFS) {
6780  return FALSE;
6781  }
6782  //
6783  // We know the bottom bits can't overflow into the pointer so just
6784  // increment
6785  //
6786  NewRef.Value = OldRef.Value + 1;
6787  NewRef.Object = InterlockedCompareExchangePointerRelease (&FastRef->Object,
6788  NewRef.Object,
6789  OldRef.Object);
6790  if (NewRef.Object != OldRef.Object) {
6791  //
6792  // The structured changed beneath us. Try the operation again
6793  //
6794  continue;
6795  }
6796  break;
6797  }
6798  return TRUE;
6799 }
6800 
6801 NTKERNELAPI
6802 LOGICAL
6803 FORCEINLINE
6804 ExFastRefAddAdditionalReferenceCounts (
6805  __inout PEX_FAST_REF FastRef,
6806  __in PVOID Object,
6807  __in ULONG RefsToAdd
6808  )
6809 /*++
6810 
6811 Routine Description:
6812 
6813  This routine attempts to update the cached references on structure to
6814  allow future callers to run lock free. Callers must have already biased
6815  the object by the RefsToAdd reference count. This operation can fail at
6816  which point the caller should removed the extra references added and
6817  continue.
6818 
6819 Arguments:
6820 
6821  FastRef - Fast reference block to be used
6822 
6823  Object - The original object that has had its reference count biased.
6824 
6825  RefsToAdd - The number of references to add to the cache
6826 
6827 Return Value:
6828 
6829  LOGICAL - TRUE: The references where cached ok, FALSE: The references
6830  could not be cached.
6831 
6832 --*/
6833 {
6834  EX_FAST_REF OldRef, NewRef;
6835 
6836  ASSERT (RefsToAdd <= MAX_FAST_REFS);
6837  ASSERT ((((ULONG_PTR)Object)&MAX_FAST_REFS) == 0);
6838 
6839  while (1) {
6840  //
6841  // Fetch the old contents of the fast ref structure
6842  //
6843  OldRef = ReadForWriteAccess(FastRef);
6844 
6845  //
6846  // If the count would push us above maximum cached references or
6847  // if the object pointer has changed the fail the request.
6848  //
6849  if (OldRef.RefCnt + RefsToAdd > MAX_FAST_REFS ||
6850  (ULONG_PTR) Object != (OldRef.Value & ~MAX_FAST_REFS)) {
6851  return FALSE;
6852  }
6853  //
6854  // We know the bottom bits can't overflow into the pointer so just
6855  // increment
6856  //
6857  NewRef.Value = OldRef.Value + RefsToAdd;
6858  NewRef.Object = InterlockedCompareExchangePointerAcquire (&FastRef->Object,
6859  NewRef.Object,
6860  OldRef.Object);
6861  if (NewRef.Object != OldRef.Object) {
6862  //
6863  // The structured changed beneath us. Use the return value from the
6864  // exchange and try it all again.
6865  //
6866  continue;
6867  }
6868  break;
6869  }
6870  return TRUE;
6871 }
6872 
6873 NTKERNELAPI
6874 EX_FAST_REF
6875 FORCEINLINE
6876 ExFastRefSwapObject (
6877  __inout PEX_FAST_REF FastRef,
6878  __in_opt PVOID Object
6879  )
6880 /*++
6881 
6882 Routine Description:
6883 
6884  This routine attempts to replace the current object with a new object.
6885  This routine must be called while holding the lock that protects the
6886  pointer field if concurrency with the slow ref path is possible.
6887  Its also possible to obtain and drop the lock after this operation has
6888  completed to force all the slow referencers from the slow reference path.
6889 
6890 Arguments:
6891 
6892  FastRef - Fast reference block to be used
6893 
6894  Object - The new object that is to be placed in the structure. This
6895  object must have already had its reference count biased by
6896  the caller to account for the reference cache.
6897 
6898 Return Value:
6899 
6900  EX_FAST_REF - The old contents of the fast reference structure.
6901 
6902 --*/
6903 {
6904  EX_FAST_REF OldRef;
6905  EX_FAST_REF NewRef;
6906 
6907  ASSERT ((((ULONG_PTR)Object)&MAX_FAST_REFS) == 0);
6908  if (Object != NULL) {
6909  NewRef.Value = (ULONG_PTR) Object | MAX_FAST_REFS;
6910  } else {
6911  NewRef.Value = 0;
6912  }
6913  OldRef.Object = InterlockedExchangePointer (&FastRef->Object, NewRef.Object);
6914  return OldRef;
6915 }
6916 
6917 NTKERNELAPI
6918 EX_FAST_REF
6919 FORCEINLINE
6920 ExFastRefCompareSwapObject (
6921  __inout PEX_FAST_REF FastRef,
6922  __in_opt PVOID Object,
6923  __in PVOID OldObject
6924  )
6925 /*++
6926 
6927 Routine Description:
6928 
6929  This routine attempts to replace the current object with a new object if
6930  the current object matches the old object.
6931  This routine must be called while holding the lock that protects the
6932  pointer field if concurrency with the slow ref path is possible.
6933  Its also possible to obtain and drop the lock after this operation has
6934  completed to force all the slow referencers from the slow reference path.
6935 
6936 Arguments:
6937 
6938  FastRef - Fast reference block to be used
6939 
6940  Object - The new object that is to be placed in the structure. This
6941  object must have already had its reference count biased by
6942  the caller to account for the reference cache.
6943 
6944  OldObject - The object that must match the current object for the
6945  swap to occur.
6946 
6947 Return Value:
6948 
6949  EX_FAST_REF - The old contents of the fast reference structure.
6950 
6951 --*/
6952 {
6953  EX_FAST_REF OldRef;
6954  EX_FAST_REF NewRef;
6955 
6956  ASSERT ((((ULONG_PTR)Object)&MAX_FAST_REFS) == 0);
6957  while (1) {
6958  //
6959  // Fetch the old contents of the fast ref structure
6960  //
6961  OldRef = ReadForWriteAccess(FastRef);
6962 
6963  //
6964  // Compare the current object to the old to see if a swap is possible.
6965  //
6966  if (!ExFastRefEqualObjects (OldRef, OldObject)) {
6967  return OldRef;
6968  }
6969 
6970  if (Object != NULL) {
6971  NewRef.Value = (ULONG_PTR) Object | MAX_FAST_REFS;
6972  } else {
6973  NewRef.Value = (ULONG_PTR) Object;
6974  }
6975 
6976  NewRef.Object = InterlockedCompareExchangePointerRelease (&FastRef->Object,
6977  NewRef.Object,
6978  OldRef.Object);
6979  if (NewRef.Object != OldRef.Object) {
6980  //
6981  // The structured changed beneath us. Try it all again.
6982  //
6983  continue;
6984  }
6985  break;
6986  }
6987  return OldRef;
6988 }

7097 /*++
7098 
7099 Routine Description:
7100 
7101  Acquire a push lock exclusively and immediately release it
7102

7104 
7105  PushLock - Push lock to be acquired and released
7106

7110

7117  KeMemoryBarrier ();

7120  ExfAcquirePushLockExclusive (PushLock);
7121  ASSERT (PushLock->Locked);
7122  ExfReleasePushLockExclusive (PushLock);
7123  }
7124 }

7161 VOID
7162 FORCEINLINE
7163 ExConvertPushLockExclusiveToShared (
7164  IN PEX_PUSH_LOCK PushLock
7165  )
7166 /*++
7167 
7168 Routine Description:
7169 
7170  Attempts to convert an exclusive acquire to shared. If other shared waiters
7171  are present at the end of the waiters chain they are released.
7172 
7173 Arguments:
7174 
7175  PushLock - Push lock to be converted
7176 
7177 Return Value:
7178 
7179  None.
7180 
7181 --*/
7182 {
7183 
7184 #if DBG
7185  EX_PUSH_LOCK OldValue;
7186 
7187  OldValue = *PushLock;
7188 
7189  ASSERT (OldValue.Waiting || OldValue.Shared == 0);
7190  ASSERT (OldValue.Locked);
7191 
7192 #endif
7193 
7194  if (InterlockedCompareExchangePointer (&PushLock->Ptr,
7195  (PVOID) (EX_PUSH_LOCK_SHARE_INC|EX_PUSH_LOCK_LOCK),
7196  (PVOID) EX_PUSH_LOCK_LOCK) !=
7197  (PVOID) EX_PUSH_LOCK_LOCK) {
7198  ExfConvertPushLockExclusiveToShared (PushLock);
7199 #if DBG
7200  OldValue = *PushLock;
7201  ASSERT (OldValue.Locked);
7202  ASSERT (OldValue.Waiting || OldValue.Shared > 0);
7203 #endif
7204  }
7205 }
7206 
7207 // begin_ntosp
7208 
7209 VOID
7210 FORCEINLINE
7211 ExAcquirePushLockExclusive (
7212  IN PEX_PUSH_LOCK PushLock
7213  )
7214 /*++
7215 
7216 Routine Description:
7217 
7218  Acquire a push lock exclusively
7219 
7220 Arguments:
7221 
7222  PushLock - Push lock to be acquired
7223 
7224 Return Value:
7225 
7226  None
7227 
7228 --*/
7229 {
7230 #if defined (_WIN64)
7231  if (InterlockedBitTestAndSet64 ((LONG64 *)&PushLock->Value, EX_PUSH_LOCK_LOCK_V))
7232 #else
7233  if (InterlockedBitTestAndSet ((LONG *)&PushLock->Value, EX_PUSH_LOCK_LOCK_V))
7234 #endif
7235  {
7236  ExfAcquirePushLockExclusive (PushLock);
7237  }
7238  ASSERT (PushLock->Locked);
7239 }
7240 
7241 BOOLEAN
7242 FORCEINLINE
7243 ExTryAcquirePushLockExclusive (
7244  IN PEX_PUSH_LOCK PushLock
7245  )
7246 /*++
7247 
7248 Routine Description:
7249 
7250  Try and acquire a push lock exclusively
7251 
7252 Arguments:
7253 
7254  PushLock - Push lock to be acquired
7255 
7256 Return Value:
7257 
7258  BOOLEAN - TRUE: Acquire was successful, FALSE: Lock was already acquired
7259 
7260 --*/
7261 {
7262 #if defined (_WIN64)
7263  if (!InterlockedBitTestAndSet64 ((LONG64 *)&PushLock->Value, EX_PUSH_LOCK_LOCK_V)) {
7264 #else
7265  if (!InterlockedBitTestAndSet ((LONG *)&PushLock->Value, EX_PUSH_LOCK_LOCK_V)) {
7266 #endif
7267  ASSERT (PushLock->Locked);
7268  return TRUE;
7269  } else {
7270  return FALSE;
7271  }
7272 }
7273 
7274 BOOLEAN
7275 FORCEINLINE
7276 ExTryAcquirePushLockShared (
7277  IN PEX_PUSH_LOCK PushLock
7278  )
7279 /*++
7280 
7281 Routine Description:
7282 
7283  Try to Acquire a push lock shared.
7284 
7285 Arguments:
7286 
7287  PushLock - Push lock to be acquired
7288 
7289 Return Value:
7290 
7291  BOOLEAN - TRUE: Acquire was successful, FALSE: Lock was already acquired exclusively.
7292 
7293 --*/
7294 {
7295  EX_PUSH_LOCK OldValue, NewValue;
7296 
7297  OldValue.Value = 0;
7298  NewValue.Value = EX_PUSH_LOCK_SHARE_INC|EX_PUSH_LOCK_LOCK;
7299 
7300  if (InterlockedCompareExchangePointer (&PushLock->Ptr,
7301  NewValue.Ptr,
7302  OldValue.Ptr) != OldValue.Ptr) {
7303  if (!ExfTryAcquirePushLockShared (PushLock)) {
7304  return FALSE;
7305  }
7306  }
7307 #if DBG
7308  OldValue = *PushLock;
7309  ASSERT (OldValue.Locked);
7310  ASSERT (OldValue.Waiting || OldValue.Shared > 0);
7311 #endif
7312  return TRUE;
7313 }

7339  NewValue.Value = EX_PUSH_LOCK_SHARE_INC|EX_PUSH_LOCK_LOCK;
7340 
7341  if (InterlockedCompareExchangePointer (&PushLock->Ptr,
7342  NewValue.Ptr,
7343  OldValue.Ptr) != OldValue.Ptr) {
7344  ExfAcquirePushLockShared (PushLock);
7345  }

7353 VOID
7354 FORCEINLINE
7355 ExAcquirePushLockSharedAssumeNoOwner (
7356  IN PEX_PUSH_LOCK PushLock
7357  )
7358 /*++
7359 
7360 Routine Description:
7361 
7362  Acquire a push lock shared making the assumption that its not currently owned.
7363 
7364 Arguments:
7365 
7366  PushLock - Push lock to be acquired
7367 
7368 Return Value:
7369 
7370  None
7371 
7372 --*/
7373 {
7374  if (InterlockedCompareExchangePointer (&PushLock->Ptr,
7375  (PVOID)(EX_PUSH_LOCK_SHARE_INC|EX_PUSH_LOCK_LOCK),
7376  NULL) != NULL) {
7377  ExfAcquirePushLockShared (PushLock);

7380 
7381 BOOLEAN
7382 FORCEINLINE
7383 ExTryConvertPushLockSharedToExclusive (
7384  IN PEX_PUSH_LOCK PushLock
7385  )
7386 /*++
7387 
7388 Routine Description:
7389 
7390  Attempts to convert a shared acquire to exclusive. If other sharers or waiters are present
7391  the function fails.
7392 
7393 Arguments:
7394 
7395  PushLock - Push lock to be converted
7396 
7397 Return Value:
7398 
7399  BOOLEAN - TRUE: Conversion worked ok, FALSE: The conversion could not be achieved
7400 
7401 --*/
7402 {
7403  if (InterlockedCompareExchangePointer (&PushLock->Ptr,
7404  (PVOID) EX_PUSH_LOCK_LOCK,
7405  (PVOID) (EX_PUSH_LOCK_SHARE_INC|EX_PUSH_LOCK_LOCK)) ==
7406  (PVOID)(EX_PUSH_LOCK_SHARE_INC|EX_PUSH_LOCK_LOCK)) {
7407  ASSERT (PushLock->Locked);
7408  return TRUE;
7409  } else {
7410  return FALSE;
7411  }
7412 }
7413 
7414 
7415 VOID
7416 FORCEINLINE
7417 ExReleasePushLock (
7418  IN PEX_PUSH_LOCK PushLock
7419  )
7420 /*++
7421 
7422 Routine Description:
7423 
7424  Release a push lock that was acquired exclusively or shared
7425 
7426 Arguments:
7427 
7428  PushLock - Push lock to be released
7429 
7430 Return Value:
7431 
7432  None
7433 
7434 --*/
7435 {
7436  EX_PUSH_LOCK OldValue, NewValue;
7437 
7438  OldValue = ReadForWriteAccess (PushLock);
7439 
7440  ASSERT (OldValue.Locked);
7441 
7442  if (OldValue.Shared > 1) {
7443  NewValue.Value = OldValue.Value - EX_PUSH_LOCK_SHARE_INC;
7444  } else {
7445  NewValue.Value = 0;
7446  }
7447 
7448  if (OldValue.Waiting ||
7449  InterlockedCompareExchangePointer (&PushLock->Ptr,
7450  NewValue.Ptr,
7451  OldValue.Ptr) != OldValue.Ptr) {
7452  ExfReleasePushLock (PushLock);
7453  }
7454 }
7455 
7456 VOID
7457 FORCEINLINE
7458 ExReleasePushLockExclusive (
7459  IN PEX_PUSH_LOCK PushLock
7460  )
7461 /*++
7462 
7463 Routine Description:
7464 
7465  Release a push lock that was acquired exclusively
7466 
7467 Arguments:
7468 
7469  PushLock - Push lock to be released
7470 
7471 Return Value:
7472 
7473  None
7474 
7475 --*/
7476 {
7477  EX_PUSH_LOCK OldValue;
7478 
7479 #if DBG
7480  OldValue = *PushLock;
7481 
7482  ASSERT (OldValue.Locked);
7483  ASSERT (OldValue.Waiting || OldValue.Shared == 0);
7484 
7485 #endif
7486 
7487 #if defined (_WIN64)
7488  OldValue.Value = InterlockedExchangeAdd64 ((PLONG64)&PushLock->Value, -(LONG64)EX_PUSH_LOCK_LOCK);
7489 #else
7490  OldValue.Value = InterlockedExchangeAdd ((PLONG)&PushLock->Value, -(LONG)EX_PUSH_LOCK_LOCK);
7491 #endif
7492 
7493  ASSERT (OldValue.Locked);
7494  ASSERT (OldValue.Waiting || OldValue.Shared == 0);
7495 
7496  if (!OldValue.Waiting || OldValue.Waking) {
7497  return;
7498  }
7499 
7500  ExfTryToWakePushLock (PushLock);
7501 }
7502 
7503 VOID
7504 FORCEINLINE
7505 ExReleasePushLockShared (
7506  IN PEX_PUSH_LOCK PushLock
7507  )
7508 /*++
7509 
7510 Routine Description:
7511 
7512  Release a push lock that was acquired shared
7513 
7514 Arguments:
7515 
7516  PushLock - Push lock to be released
7517 
7518 Return Value:
7519 
7520  None
7521 
7522 --*/
7523 {
7524  EX_PUSH_LOCK OldValue, NewValue;
7525 
7526 #if DBG
7527 
7528  OldValue = *PushLock;
7529 
7530  ASSERT (OldValue.Locked);
7531  ASSERT (OldValue.Waiting || OldValue.Shared > 0);
7532 
7533 #endif
7534 
7535  OldValue.Value = EX_PUSH_LOCK_SHARE_INC|EX_PUSH_LOCK_LOCK;
7536  NewValue.Value = 0;
7537 
7538  if (InterlockedCompareExchangePointer (&PushLock->Ptr,
7539  NewValue.Ptr,
7540  OldValue.Ptr) != OldValue.Ptr) {
7541  ExfReleasePushLockShared (PushLock);
7542  }
7543 }

7545 VOID
7546 FORCEINLINE
7547 ExReleasePushLockSharedAssumeSingleOwner (
7548  IN PEX_PUSH_LOCK PushLock
7549  )
7550 /*++
7551 
7552 Routine Description:
7553 
7554  Release a push lock that was acquired shared assuming that we are the only owner
7555 
7556 Arguments:
7557 
7558  PushLock - Push lock to be released
7559 
7560 Return Value:
7561 
7562  None
7563 
7564 --*/
7565 {
7566 #if DBG
7567  EX_PUSH_LOCK OldValue;
7568 
7569  OldValue = *PushLock;
7570 
7571  ASSERT (OldValue.Locked);
7572  ASSERT (OldValue.Waiting || OldValue.Shared > 0);
7573 
7574 #endif
7575 
7576  if (InterlockedCompareExchangePointer (&PushLock->Ptr,
7577  NULL,
7578  (PVOID)(EX_PUSH_LOCK_SHARE_INC|EX_PUSH_LOCK_LOCK)) !=
7579  (PVOID)(EX_PUSH_LOCK_SHARE_INC|EX_PUSH_LOCK_LOCK)) {
7580  ExfReleasePushLockShared (PushLock);
7581  }
7582 }

7689 FORCEINLINE
7690 ExAcquireCacheAwarePushLockShared (
7691  IN PEX_PUSH_LOCK_CACHE_AWARE CacheAwarePushLock
7692  )
7693 /*++
7694 
7695 Routine Description:
7696 
7697  Acquire a cache aware push lock shared.
7698 
7699 Arguments:
7700 
7701  PushLock - Cache aware push lock to be acquired
7702 
7703 Return Value:
7704 
7705  None
7706 
7707 --*/
7708 {
7709  PEX_PUSH_LOCK PushLock;
7710  //
7711  // Take a single one of the slots in shared mode.
7712  // Exclusive acquires must obtain all the slots exclusive.
7713  //

7715  ExAcquirePushLockSharedAssumeNoOwner (PushLock);
7716  return PushLock;
7717 }

7733

7739 {

7742  return;
